\b 2. What are the different types of web servers, and how do they differ in terms of functionality and performance?\par
Ans: \b0 There are several types of web servers available, each with its own strengths and weaknesses in terms of functionality and performance. Some of the most common types of web servers are:\par
Apache HTTP Server: Apache is the most widely used web server in the world, and it is an open-source web server that can run on a variety of platforms, including Unix, Linux, and Windows. Apache is known for its reliability, stability, and flexibility, and it is highly configurable.\par
Nginx: Nginx is a lightweight, high-performance web server that is designed to handle a large number of concurrent connections efficiently. Nginx is known for its speed, scalability, and stability, and it is commonly used as a reverse proxy, load balancer, or HTTP cache.\par
Microsoft IIS: IIS is a web server developed by Microsoft, and it is designed to run on the Windows operating system. IIS is known for its integration with other Microsoft technologies, such as ASP.NET, and it is often used in enterprise environments.\par
Lighttpd: Lighttpd is a lightweight, high-performance web server that is designed to handle a large number of concurrent connections efficiently. Lighttpd is known for its speed and scalability, and it is commonly used for serving static content or as a reverse proxy.\par
Google Web Server (GWS): GWS is a web server developed by Google, and it is used to serve content for many of Google's web services, such as Google Search and Google Maps. GWS is highly optimized for serving dynamic content, and it is known for its speed and reliability.\par
In terms of functionality, web servers differ in their capabilities to handle different types of requests and protocols, such as HTTP, HTTPS, and FTP. They may also have different security features, such as SSL/TLS encryption and firewalls.\par
In terms of performance, web servers differ in their ability to handle a large number of concurrent connections, their speed in serving static and dynamic content, and their ability to handle high traffic loads. Factors such as the server hardware, network bandwidth, and server configuration can also affect the performance of a web server.\par
